nd some of the skillful collectors let parts ofthe root remain in the deep sand to hope that a new plant grows from that. This hope is not quite unfounded and some people have already dug out the Glyvir root at the same place over years. You cut the root corm into thin slices and let them dry afterwards. During the accordant ritual these thin slices will be dug in the ground at the place of ceremony together with goldenrod powder. Thereby the god of fertility will be made merciful and the yield of herbal resources will considerably increase in the next time.§($2,<,-1) §§
